</code></pre></div></div>
<p>go to local host you should see that the changes to the title of the page have been made! FUN!</p>

<p>Next we are Going to Edit the About Me Page</p>

<p>In the root of your directory you should see a about.html. this is what we are going to edit. By default it includes a lot of helpful links, so I recommend checking them out before deleting them. You will see some elements in between -â€“ lines. This is called <a href="https://jekyllrb.com/docs/front-matter/">front matter</a> which we will get into later. Iâ€™ve updated and saved and gone to localhost:4000/about/</p>

<p><img src="\pictures\how I Created My Blog\installjekyll8.png" /></p>

<p>If you want to add a picture you can use the HTML &lt;img&gt; tag.</p>

<p>I first in root created a directory named _pictures and the _ lets Jekyll know that this folder is included in the _site</p>

<p>Now I am going to show you the about.html page for this blog.</p>

<p><img src="\pictures\how I Created My Blog\installjekyll9.png" /></p>

<p>Iâ€™m feeling so exposed now!
Basically this is my current file structure and if you navigate to my About page this is what the md file for the page looks like. Iâ€™ve inserted my image using an HTML tag and the rest is writing in pretty plane English.</p>

<p><strong><em>Front matter</em></strong></p>

<p>Front matter in my FM you can see I have a Layout option. if you go to the _layouts folder you will see post.html. I like to think of the layout variable as a wrapper for how  everything inside of my _post folder.
Next you see the title variable. I feel like this is pretty self explanatory.
and then you have the permalink variable, this lets Jekyll know what page to navigate to inside the directory.</p>

<p><strong><em>CSS</em></strong></p>

<p>ok so now we wanna edit some style of the blog this first thing I di was change colors around. I navigated to the localhost:4000 and once there I right clicked and clicked inspect.
This will help guide you too the css elements you want to change.
<img src="\pictures\how I Created My Blog\installjekyll010.png" />
As you scroll over the element it will highlight which section is covers, Im going to get specific enough so that I  only have the site tile highlighted. This is what I see:</p>

<p><img src="\pictures\how I Created My Blog\installjekyll011.png" /></p>

<p>under the styles tab to the right in the .site-title, .site-vistied box we see the file and the line we need to go to to change that element. In this case layout.css:26. so back in Atom i will go to \sass &gt; minima &gt; _layout.css &gt; line 26 aka .site-title{} and insert color: #99ff33;</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>  .site-title {
    @include relative-font-size(1.625);
    font-weight: 300;
    letter-spacing: -1px;
    margin-bottom: 0;
    float: left;
    color: #99ff33;
    @include media-query($on-palm) {
      padding-right: 45px;
    }

  &amp;,
  &amp;:visited {
    color: #99ff33;
  }
}
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>now itâ€™s Lime Green.
I Continued to do this for my site-nav, post-headings, and post-links.</p>

